2024-08-25

We will be predicting the likelihood a customer will leave the company otherwise known as ‘churn’

telco <- read.csv("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1GbUzso0rHde2YjI3UDAVhJLgAIPz26uIoGL6EdFwSQw/export?format=csv", stringsAsFactors = TRUE)

names(telco)
##  [1] "Gender"           "SeniorCitizen"    "Partner"          "Dependents"       "tenure"           "PhoneService"     "MultipleLines"    "InternetService"  "OnlineSecurity"   "OnlineBackup"    
## [11] "DeviceProtection" "TechSupport"      "StreamingTV"      "StreamingMovies"  "Contract"         "PaperlessBilling" "PaymentMethod"    "MonthlyCharges"   "TotalCharges"     "Churn"
splits <- initial_split(telco)

telco_train <- training(splits)
telco_test <- testing(splits)
telco_recipe <- recipe(Churn ~ ., data = telco_train) %>%
  step_YeoJohnson(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_corr(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_lincomb(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_nzv(all_numeric_predictors())

telco_recipe %>%
  prep()

Using the GLMNET and forest model here with some values.

telco_glmnet <- logistic_reg(
  engine = "glmnet",
  penalty = 0.01,
  mixture = 0.5
)

telco_forest <- rand_forest(
  mode = "classification",
  mtry = 5
) %>% set_engine(engine = "ranger", importance = "impurity")

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

telco_glmnet_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(telco_recipe) %>%
  add_model(telco_glmnet)

telco_forest_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(telco_recipe) %>%
  add_model(telco_forest)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

fit_glmnet <- telco_glmnet_workflow %>% 
  fit(telco_train)

fit_forest <- telco_forest_workflow %>% 
  fit(telco_train)

Finding the five most important features for prediction

Here we notice the features of importance differ between the two models. The two features that remain in common between the two are InternetService_Fiber.optic and Contract_Two.year

vip_telco_forest <- telco_forest_workflow %>% 
  finalize_workflow(telco_forest_workflow) %>% 
  fit(telco_train)

vip(vip_telco_forest, num_features = 5)

vip_telco_glmnet <- telco_glmnet_workflow %>% 
  finalize_workflow(telco_glmnet_workflow) %>% 
  fit(telco_train)

vip(vip_telco_glmnet, num_features = 5)

We can see the forest model performed with an accuracy of 0.91 on the train and 0.79 on the test suggesting it may be overfit whereas the glmnet model performed with an accuracy of around 0.8 on both the train and test suggesting it is a good fit. With this in mind, we the glmnet is the better model.
